# Intuition
As we always need to get the worker with mininum cost and index we can use a Priority Queue and add candidates from first and last respectively.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
After Creating a Min Heap `pq`
We add first `candidates` from the begin.
And if we still have space we try adding `candidates` from last.

Using the Min Head we pop workers and add there cost and by using the workers index we add cost from begin or end.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: *`O(k * log(candidates))`*
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: *`O(candidates)`*
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long totalCost(vector<int>& costs, int k, int candidates) {
        long long cost = 0;
        priority_queue<pair<int, int>, vector<pair<int, int>>, greater<pair<int, int>>> pq;

        int n = costs.size();
        int l, r;

        for(int i = 0; i < candidates; i++)
            pq.push(make_pair(costs[i], i));

        l = candidates - 1;
        r = max(candidates, n - candidates);

        for(int i = r; i < n; i++)
            pq.push(make_pair(costs[i], i));

        int ind;
        while(k--) {
            cost += pq.top().first;
            ind = pq.top().second;
            pq.pop();

            if(ind <= l && (l + 1) < r) { // begin
                l++;
                pq.push(make_pair(costs[l], l));
            }
            else if(ind >= r && (r - 1) > l) { // end
                r--;
                pq.push(make_pair(costs[r], r));
            }
        }


        return cost;
    }
};
```

