# Intuition
This problem can be solved by using priority queue and some mathematics.
Lets suppose there are m candidates
Initialise i=0,j=n-1;
Firstly we push cost of first m candidates from begin and from last along with their indces in priority queue by incrementing i and decrementing j ( such that no element is pushed twice, we check for condition i<candidates).
So, while k (workers count > 0 ) we increase cost by top element of priority queue.(minimum cost among first m candidates and last m candidates) and check for what index of element is poped. If that index is greater that j implies that poped candidates is from end so push one candidate from end(i.e,jth  as after this already pushed ) and decrement j.
else poped candidates is from begin so push one candidate from begin(ith) and increment i.
repeat until k>0.
return cost.



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
// TC - O((k)Log(2*Candidates)) + O(Candidates)


- Space complexity:
// SC - O(2*Candidates)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
   # define ll long long
    long long totalCost(vector<int>& costs, int k, int candidates) {

        int n=costs.size();
        if(n==1) return costs[0];
        int i=0,j=n-1;
        long long cost=0;

        priority_queue<pair<int,int>,vector<pair<int,int>>,greater<pair<int,int>>>pq;
        while(i<j && i<candidates ){
              pq.push({costs[i],i});
              pq.push({costs[j],j});
              i++;j--;
        }

        while(k>0){
           int ind=pq.top().second;
           cost+=(ll)pq.top().first;
           pq.pop(); //cout<<ind<<" "<<i<<" "<<j<<endl;
           if(i<=j){ 
               if(ind>j){
                   pq.push({costs[j],j});
                   j--;
               }
               else{
                   pq.push({costs[i],i});
                   i++;
               }
           } //cout<<cost<<endl;
           k--;
        }
        return cost;
    }
};
```

